"Helm K.P., Bindoff N.L., Church J.A.","Observed decreases in oxygen content of the global ocean",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","23", L23602,"","",,,10.1029/2011GL049513,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-82955177041&partnerID=40&md5=1d68b75ba50922fa063318fbf497801c","Institute of Marine and Antarctic Studies, University of Tasmania, Hobart, TAS 7001, Australia; University of Tasmania Antarctic Climate, Ecosystems Cooperative Research Centre, Hobart, TAS, Australia; CAWCR, GPO Box 1538, Hobart, TAS 7001, Australia; Wealth from Oceans Flagship, Hobart, TAS, Australia","Helm, K.P., Institute of Marine and Antarctic Studies, University of Tasmania, Hobart, TAS 7001, Australia, University of Tasmania Antarctic Climate, Ecosystems Cooperative Research Centre, Hobart, TAS, Australia; Bindoff, N.L., Institute of Marine and Antarctic Studies, University of Tasmania, Hobart, TAS 7001, Australia, University of Tasmania Antarctic Climate, Ecosystems Cooperative Research Centre, Hobart, TAS, Australia, CAWCR, GPO Box 1538, Hobart, TAS 7001, Australia, Wealth from Oceans Flagship, Hobart, TAS, Australia; Church, J.A., University of Tasmania Antarctic Climate, Ecosystems Cooperative Research Centre, Hobart, TAS, Australia, CAWCR, GPO Box 1538, Hobart, TAS 7001, Australia","Comparing the high-quality oxygen climatology from the World Ocean Circulation Experiment to earlier data we reveal near-global decreases in oxygen levels in the upper ocean between the 1970s and the 1990s. This globally averaged oxygen decrease is-0.93 ± 0.23 μmol l-1, which is equivalent to annual oxygen losses of-0.55 ± 0.13 × 1014 mol yr-1 (100-1000 m). The strongest decreases in oxygen occur in the mid-latitudes of both hemispheres, near regions where there is strong water renewal and exchange between the ocean interior and surface waters. Approximately 15% of global oxygen decrease can be explained by a warmer mixed-layer reducing the capacity of water to store oxygen, while the remainder is consistent with an overall decrease in the exchange between surface waters and the ocean interior. Here we suggest that this reduction in water mass renewal rates on a global scale is a consequence of increased stratification caused by warmer surface waters. These observations support climate model simulations of oxygen change under global warming scenarios. © 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Climate models; Climatology; Computer simulation; Global warming; Oceanography; Surface waters; Climate model simulations; Global ocean; Global scale; High quality; Midlatitudes; Oxygen content; Oxygen levels; Oxygen loss; Upper ocean; Water mass; Water renewal; World Ocean Circulation Experiment; Oxygen; climate modeling; climatology; global ocean; global warming; latitude; mixed layer; numerical model; observational method; oxygen; surface water; water exchange; water mass",,,,,,"Aoki, S., Bindoff, N.L., Church, J.A., Interdecadal water mass changes in the Southern Ocean between 30E and 160E (2005) Geophysical Research Letters, 32 (7), pp. 1-5. , DOI 10.1029/2004GL022220, L07607; Bindoff, N.L., McDougall, T.J., Diagnosing climate-change and ocean ventilation using hydrographic data (1994) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 24 (6), pp. 1137-1152. , doi:10.1175/1520-0485(1994)024〈1137:DCCAOV〉2. 0.CO;2; Bindoff, N.L., McDougall, T.J., Decadal changes along an Indian Ocean section at 32S and their interpretation (2000) Journal of Physical Oceanography, 30 (6), pp. 1207-1222; Bindoff, N.L., Observations: Oceanic climate change and sea level (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group i to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 385-432. , edited by S. Solomon et al. chap. 5 Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Bopp, L., Le Quéré, C., Heimann, M., Manning, A.C., Monfray, P., Climate-induced oceanic oxygen fluxes: Implications for the contemporary carbon budget (2002) Global Biogeochem. Cycles